Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to search among the stars related, that is, those that arose from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and briefly they can be found on the university's website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the gas clouds that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of relative stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer simulated two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
This object within a few million years, under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added label paints to the original gas streams and found that due to rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud, a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for relative stars by chemical composition, as well as to determine the possible regions of formation of such objects.
