Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that would protect union organization as a civil right.
"Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Progressive Caucus Congress.
That's why I'm proud to introduce the Workers' Empowerment Act along with civil rights movement symbol John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal options for discrimination against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of union opponents.
Amending the Labour Relations Regulation Act to allow workers facing discrimination for their participation in trade union organisations to seek justice in the civil courts – and to receive damages and punitive payments – is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the bill's co-sponsors are proposing is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks unions have faced in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once supported countries around the world in embracing, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, free speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drafted to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, and to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that explicitly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe on this right will have no legal effect; measures aimed at that purpose would be found to be unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was Chair of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect his interests."
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize unions — and to have that union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — must be protected.
At a time when these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, unions miraculously created a market for industry and lifted an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how we should.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human rights – and greater protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against trade union organisations – is long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis are reviving ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Shut Down All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana
In the U.S., a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of a Louisiana law that his supporters say it is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Gov. Bobby Ginadl in June and was set to take effect Sept. 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to see patients at a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that for now, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
"Plaintiffs will be permitted to work legally while continuing to obtain authority," Judge John deGravells wrote in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which the judge will issue a more permanent ruling on the law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a string of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital credentials.
"Today's decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who were not plaintiffs in the case and had also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in that state were blocked by a federal judge Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws impose medical restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the other doctors on staff were forced to stop performing the procedure, that doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission credentials await a decision.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to?
At least half of the products for each type of product in the range of retail chains should be of Russian production, said Oleg Nilov, a State Duma deputy from the Fair Russia faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, the Izvestia newspaper writes.
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. <...> For the remaining groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers," Nilov told the publication.
Together with amendments to the article "On the Basics of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea to introduce a 50% quota in retail chains is included in the package of incentive measures for Russian producers.
Several times more domestic goods will appear on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company "Tax", a member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" Sergey Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
In the black will be agricultural producers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian producers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be developed faster, and will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, although not immediately," the expert said.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into the shelves of local stores due to high competition from foreign analogues.
Now, after the introduction of the embargo, this niche has been vacated and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now is the "lull moment", when the old players have already left, and the new ones have not yet come.
After almost a month, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as an increase in prices for finished products," Tamara Kasyanova, First Vice-President of the All-Russian Public Organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", Candidate of Economic Sciences, told AiF.ru.
Definitely, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow the sector to be assigned to local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that, due to subsidies from another state, are cheaper.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will unfold between companies operating according to the uniform laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots not in all respects.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, fears are growing that low-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of those produced in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied," the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large retail chains, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in this situation, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to inflate the prices of the second, as a scarce product.
Economists again started talking about the idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, in February of this year due to the incessant devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more relevant.
The law is designed to oblige retailers to take into account domestic producers when forming orders.
Then we will go along the path of import substitution much faster and more confidently, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," says MP Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example, in the dairy sector, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to completely cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can also receive a powerful impetus.
As you know, the largest share of imports remains for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still falls on Russian products," Kasyanova argues.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, since this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that full-fledged import substitution will not happen, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas, it is also necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees," the expert states.
Late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James posted a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who survive in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
Researchers analysed disease maps of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that just 35 per cent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Institute for Medical Research Berghofer reported that those living in regions and remote areas of the state are 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
SMALL STUDY: New Drugs May Slow Lung and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers traced the women's medical path over seven years.
Dr Jordan said the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those with cancer were at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons who specialize in gynecological oncology, and they are mostly in big cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of on-site services that will allow specialists to treat women closer to home and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home could help.
Dr Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Niv, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
