Inflation is out of vacation.
Will Russians feel a sharp increase in prices?
As a result of cross-sanctions of the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the forecasts of the authorities, analysts of VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year and even less - 6.5%.
However, according to the newspaper Kommersant, this week the Ministry of Economic Development should make "small but fundamental" adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zeroing of income growth of the population.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How, in such a situation, could such high inflation be assumed?
The current situation suggests a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change," the newspaper's source in the Ministry of Finance said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the financial and economic bloc of the government regarding inflation and predict price growth in 2014 at the level of 8%.
The main effect of food bans will come along with the possible introduction of a sales tax (NSP) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
The inflation peak of 9% will be in February, after which the annual growth rate of prices will decline, experts say.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation introduced "careful sanctions".
AiF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of Analytical Department of AForex FC:
Price growth is already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially significant products began to rise in price, the government was forced to launch measures of systematic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason is initiating the price increase.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal rates of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as the embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures had remained under control, the value of the basket of the minimum set of products would not have jumped by 12% in just one quarter.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a completely logical increase in the final cost.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to bear the risks of an increase in the inflation component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorated prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvaev, Director of Alpari's Analytical Department
In the 90s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in the zero it was also higher than the current level, another thing is that then it was compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think that by the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, Asset Manager, Maguta Fund Management Company
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia has so far been successfully restrained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector, this may lead to certain difficulties and increase inflation expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in purchases of cash currency in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and state regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer lull and, perhaps, this autumn will become more noticeable.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to survive, since the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Horticultural centers are saddened by the decline in the number of homeowners
Such a drop, driven by an exceptional reduction in the number of homeowners under the age of 35, could cause horticultural centres to start losing tens of millions of pounds a year as today's young consumers reach the "basic age of horticulture", according to an HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, people renting a home spend an average of 55 percent of the amount that owners of their own homes spend on gardening.
It cites an increase in the number of people living in highly urbanised areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting yards in front of a parking house and a shrinking garden as other factors posing a threat to the industry, which has an estimated £5 billion in annual sales.
Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, has the lowest level of spending on gardeners' goods per household in the UK.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society said renting and not having space for a garden didn't mean people couldn't grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief horticulture adviser at RHS, said: "Growing plants in containers, for example, is particularly popular with tenants who can transport plants with them when they move. "
The HTA report identified the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of retail horticultural goods as a result of increased homeowner numbers and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year thanks to better weather after unfavorable conditions in March and April last year.
The Ministry of Agriculture of Bulgaria conducted a massive purge in the fund "Agriculture"
Three of the four chiefs of the Agriculture Foundation were replaced on Friday.
In total, three of the four chiefs of the Agriculture Foundation were replaced on Friday.
