The first day of spring is marked by wet and windy conditions that affected flights at Adelaide Airport
SPRING has prepared a cold surprise in the south of South Australia, bringing torrential rains and strong winds that affected flights at Adelaide Airport.
Another 5 mm of rain fell on the city in the evening by 9 pm, following the 6.6 mm that fell during Sunday night.
The last rain was preceded by a couple of short showers with gusty winds, including a thunderstorm that began shortly before 8 pm and poured out almost 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter produced an early dose of spring last week, temperatures fell again on Monday to a maximum of just 15.8C in the city.
Squally conditions are believed to have been one of the reasons for the delay in the landing of a Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was supposed to land on schedule just after 7:30 p.m., but was caught in a zone of wind shear — a sudden change in wind speed or direction over a short distance — and was forced to gain altitude.
Wind gusts reached 50 km/h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at this time.
Flight data showed that the plane had to gain altitude during the second landing, and the plane eventually landed around 8:40 p.m.
The delay of this flight caused the subsequent delay of several other flights, including an Emirates flight from Dubai and a Qantas flight from Sydney.
A high of 16C is forecast in Adelaide on Tuesday with a chance of one or two showers.
Calculation of the estimate of construction projects in the Russian Federation will take place in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control over pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connecting to networks.
An expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector has been established under the FAS.
At its meeting, the head of the Department for Control of Housing and Communal Services, Construction and Natural Resources of the FAS Vadim Solovyov said that "today's calculation of the estimate of construction projects is absolutely incomprehensible."
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to an unreasonable construction price, according to the FAS.
And they propose to determine the cost of construction of state property facilities at the design stage on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the estimated norms and single prices for technological operations used today.
These proposals are included in the "road map" and are now under consideration in the Ministry of Construction.
"Replacing the traditional estimate documentation in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry," Vadim Solovyov explained to RSL.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors" in the documentation.
The Ministry of Construction agrees with the FAS.
"The first developments on the transition to calculating the cost of structural elements already exist: methods have been developed for calculating prices for constructive solutions, drawing up estimates for these indicators," Elena Zhukova, head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction, told RSL.
The sphere of road construction was chosen as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company Profi-Invest Anatoly Demyanko told RSL, the estimated standards have long been outdated, but no other mechanism has yet been offered to business.
"As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, in practice it is difficult to implement, since completely different technologies are often used in the construction of buildings," he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely due to the state order.
According to Ekaterina Lezina, Chairman of the Board of np "Expert Community of Public Procurement Professionals", today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, Deputy Director for Engineering of the Industry Center for Capital Construction of Rosatom, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts, and companies that own monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors in this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is protected as much as possible from someone's controlling influence.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a system of state order in such a way that the same executor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion rubles. or several contracts worth more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be assessed in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to endow the customer with the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the staff of the customer and budget costs for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer's specialists will have to have knowledge that allows them to assess the quality of the work performed by contractors, as well as their safety.
Often, with such a breakdown, it will be necessary to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the object as a whole.
In addition, this approach may entail an outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to disinterest in obtaining a state order for an incomplete amount of work and a small contract amount.
Alexander Evstashenkov, deputy head of the expert and consulting center of the Procurement Institute, believes that now the state order procedure has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave the following example: "the participant, when filling out the application, must indicate "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "should be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "similar type", "not lower", "below", "above", "may", "may have", "maybe", "earlier", "not earlier", "not higher", "not allowed", etc.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of the application submitted by contractors.
Another problem of 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the "paper" proposal of the participant at the stage of submitting an application.
Considering the application of the participant, it is possible to assess only the qualifications of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, the implementation of which has not even begun yet, the expert believes.
The quality of work can be assessed only when they are accepted.
The expert council also proposed to transfer marginal income from the upper to the lower echelon so that intermediate contractors disappear.
Chairman of the Expert Council, State Secretary, Deputy Head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it will turn out, as in the famous reprise of Arkady Raikin "Atelier": "Are there any complaints about the buttons?".
Israeli children return to school after gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from the fighting.
The start of school brought a sense of joy and excitement to the rocket-affected settlements in southern Israel, but the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed traces of shrapnel from walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
"We are a little afraid, but we look to the future with joy," said Ronit Barth, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was "a little weird" to start going back to school.
"It was a difficult time and we didn't leave our homes at all," she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the gaza border, to express his support.
Before a ceasefire stopped the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not take to the streets or fled their homes, moving to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a fragment of a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should go back.
The Ministry of Education said about a dozen families still had not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the gaza border that has been hard hit by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, "We will do everything we can to give you knowledge and keep you safe."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately ended the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for an end to the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and recover the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2100 Palestinians were killed in the war, among whom three-quarters were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to substantiate this allegation.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4591 rockets and mortars at Israeli cities, mainly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
Israeli attacks have damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools, which have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials delayed the start of the school year last week.
"I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a Gaza school.
According to a popular criterion, real estate prices showed the largest winter increase in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic housing price index for house prices in the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
This increase led to a cumulative increase for June, July and August of 4.2 percent, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
Annual price growth was 10.9 percent, more than double the increase in the 12 months to August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data research director Tim Lawless said Sydney and Melbourne are leading a two-tier market.
Figures from RP Data show that sydney house prices rose 16.1 per cent over the past year, while Melbourne has risen 11.7 per cent.
The next most powerful markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose by an average of five to six percent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which saw government spending cuts, where prices rose just 1.4 percent in a year.
Mr Lawless said that now that spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of properties for sale over the next few months, which will be a "real test" for the market.
"Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales and the current low-interest rate conditions, it is likely that the cost of housing will rise further over the next three months," he said.
How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of gold miners and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on October Revolution Street 57/1 (former Bolshaya Kazanskaya) there are 18 apartments.
The house of the XVIII century since the time of construction has not changed much, except for dilapidation.
Strangers go here as if on an excursion, and the tenants suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is almost 300 years old.
Old courtyard, always open door, creaky staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls are cracked, and the street is visible in the gaps from the peeling plaster in places.
Everything seems to be based on an honest word.
And the locals assure: "You don't think it is."
Living in a wooden house of the XVIII century is very difficult, - says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
The object is under state protection, but money for its maintenance has not been allocated for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits, which the authorities simply forgot.
The last renovation was 40 years ago.
The walls are still barely holding, but the foundation is all rotten.
Many residents still go to the toilet outside, and wash once a week in a public bath.
How can you be satisfied in such conditions?!
The road passes right under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was previously only audible: a stream of cars rushes under the windows.
You see, the glass rattles constantly, we cannot open the windows, but we are used to noise.
A person gets used to everything, to good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Moreover, we have two rooms, we live in three with our son.
And for other families, the conditions are much worse, on the second floor in general the ceilings are a little more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana suggests visiting a neighbor from apartment No. 6 Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman from the threshold offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile says:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m² for four people, and we live like this: my husband and I and my daughter and granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space - Lyudmila looks around the room: mezzanine, two sofas with the letter "g"; one of them housed a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very cramped and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But it regularly flows from the ceiling: the plumbing system is no good.
Lyudmila speaks about her apartment in an ordinary and surprising way at the same time, like an Italian woman whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it brings into one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The water pipeline was carried out about 40 years ago during the last repair.
At the same time, they made us a small kitchen in the corner and a toilet from the former closet.
We live exactly where Demidov and his family lived, and servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The Ufa Real Estate Center says privatization does not matter.
Anyway, we will get only a one-room apartment, we can not claim more.
Four months ago, they promised to resettle us, but it did not go further than promises.
I'm not used to complaining and I won't.
A whole dynasty lived in this apartment (room!): my grandparents, my mother and father, me and my husband and my daughter and granddaughter.
Stuff happened during that time.
For example, hefty rats ran around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are a meter thick!
They say the solution was mixed into the eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house is built thoroughly, thanks to the Demidovs!
Probably, that's the only reason so far no one has been killed by a collapsed ceiling or pile.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house rot, the floors have repeatedly failed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, as in a well.
They say so - under our room there is a secret manhole and a passage to the Belaya River, which was specially made by the Old Believers who once lived here, so that they could hide from danger, in case of anything.
They were persecuted.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begged them to let him begin excavations in the apartment.
And then he persuaded them to give them housing in exchange for his one on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where do the four of us go?
And here at least there is a tiny hope that they will give housing more spacious.
Had we agreed to the exchange, we would not have won anything.
However, the Starostin family did not win anything.
Lyudmila's biggest dream is to be resettled, and her daughter and her 16-year-old granddaughter were given a separate room.
That is, two families were allocated a two-room apartment instead of not the most majestic ruins, in which two generations live now.
A pretty, petite girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two cramped rooms with a total area of 23 m², called apartments, her large family lives.
There are seven of us in total, two children.
You can see for yourself what the conditions are.
Plaster falls off in pieces, like window frames, there are through holes in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms.
The water in the tap all year round is only cold.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, you can make sure that the Lavrentyev spouses from apartment No. 4 were the luckiest.
They occupy the most spacious rooms of the first floor.
You're right, there's a lot of space!
A room of 75 squares, three people are registered.
We live just in those rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One thing is bad - everything around is bursting at the seams, falling apart, collapsing.
Neighbors have probably already told!
Most of the torment we have with the floors: the wooden boards rotted, the ground literally went from under our feet.
I put up supports, wedges; there is still nothing in the hall, and in another room we walk like swinging on a swing, everything is so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell about the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov better than any guide.
He treats the gold miner as if he were his own, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was outstanding: the owner of the Kagin and Uzyansk factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, and held the Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around there were wooden rooms for carriages, stables and guard booths, subsequently demolished.
In 1968, they wanted to clean our house, but something prevented us from...
History repeated itself in 2014: they again beckoned with new housing.
We, as if on cue, collected all the documents, ran around the necessary authorities, and suddenly learned that the move to the apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
Something we no longer believe in all this...
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
Officials did not accept the tenant.
They sent it from one table to another, and then, as if in mockery, they issued a piece of paper without a signature and seal: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of tenants."
I even have a feeling that our house has long been gone from the city plan, because at first it was at number 57, then it became 57 A, and now it is 57/1.
It's like it's already been demolished in the '70s.
"Russian Planet" appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the Department for Land Resources of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house on Oktyabrskaya Revolyutsii Street 57/1 is included in the program of resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I cannot be responsible for the actions of officials of the 70s, I only know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old houses along the October Revolution Street, which are of architectural value, is being successfully implemented.
Residents are soon planned to be resettled in new apartments.
According to Barabash, italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice will restore the Demidov House.
Now an architectural biennale is taking place in Italy, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016 the entire former Old KazanSkaya Street will be restored," the official said.
The houses will acquire a proper look, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
Demidov's house is likely to become a museum open to all comers.
In addition, at the government level, it was decided to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
On weekdays, unfortunately, it will not work, too much congestion of roads in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to resettle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, it is unlikely that they will be satisfied: their new apartments will be the same area as the current ones.
Only from a different era.
In Primorye, because of a thunderstorm, a forest fire began
A dry thunderstorm caused a forest fire on the territory of the Hunting District Forestry in the Pozharsky District of the Primorsky Territory.
At the site of the fire, a grouping of forces and means is being built up.
According to the management of the Primorsky Air Base, the conditions created at the scene of the fire require the involvement of aviation forces.
Vasily Medvedev, Deputy Head of the Air Base:
The fire, which arose in a hard-to-reach area, was detected by an observer pilot from the An-2 patrol aircraft on an area of 3 hectares.
Wood residues on the old burner are burning.
The strong clutter of the territory and the steepness of the slope of more than 45 degrees, the lack of firefighters suitable for landing paratroopers create significant difficulties in extinguishing.
