4 Tips on How to Get Better Quality Underwater Photos and Videos
If you want to take pictures or shoot videos underwater, there are a number of equipment options in front of you.
The cheapest option is a waterproof soap dish like the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera like the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which sell for around $300.
I took these pictures at a family holiday with a few cameras, all priced at around $350.
No matter what equipment you use, a few rules need to be followed in order to achieve the best results.
Double-check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the camera battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, set up your camera for the type of photos or videos you'll be taking.
Some cameras and camcorders have shooting or subject type modes that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before you jump into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can sink.
Some cameras are only 5 feet long, others are 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our buyer's guide and digital camera ratings for both traditional and waterproof models.
Shoot a few shots - because many of them will not work.
"Soapboxes" have LCD that will help you put together pictures, whereas action cameras usually do not.
Even if you have an LCD, it will be difficult to see underwater, and the layout of the frame will be a random process.
So take a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a burst mode that shoots multiple shots with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay on the surface.
The amount of light is significantly reduced the deeper you dive under the water.
If possible, stay close to the surface when you're shooting in a pool, river, or ocean.
This will also allow you to convey more color in the photos; the deeper you go, the less color you'll see.
Swim closer to your subjects.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but it's even more important underwater due to the darkened light conditions.
Especially important if you're shooting with an action camera: This equipment is often equipped with a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means you'll have to get close to your subjects if you want to fill the frame.
