The results of the X-rays came.
It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or the lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it is difficult to figure out the exact cause.
Although some smokers develop lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But it's different with mesothelioma.
In almost all cases, the cause is contact with asbestos, a fibrous building material that was once called a "miracle" but which is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is material from the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when an industry ban came into force.
Even when it was in use, only people from specific industries worked closely with it: pipe insulators, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it is hardly seen as a cause for concern today.
But such calmness is wrong.
The UK, it turns out, is now at the peak of the mesothelioma epidemic.
More people die from mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
