The Ministry of Economic Development wants to accelerate the growth of the electric vehicle market
This week, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit to the government a comprehensive plan for the development of environmentally friendly transport in Russia, said Oleg Pluzhnikov, deputy director of the ministry's department, at a round table held by Vedomosti at the Moscow Motor Show - 2014.
The plan was drawn up on behalf of the government, one of the main goals is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
It is expected that the document will be adopted in late September - early October, says Pluzhnikov, the proposed measures relate to electric vehicles and hybrids - a plan for the development of vehicles on gas engine fuel in Russia already exists.
The plan (Vedomosti has a copy) is designed for 2014-2017.
It is necessary to develop criteria for the evaluation of electric and hybrid transport and decide how to stimulate the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
A report to the government describing tax and customs measures to support electric transport will be prepared by December 2014; the scheme of preferential lending and preferential leasing will appear by April 2015; and proposals to reduce the price of machines, stimulate localization and create a service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015, it is planned to amend the regulatory legal acts in order to facilitate the conditions for the construction of charging infrastructure (in parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend to formulate proposals for regional authorities during 2015 that they also stimulate the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of giving it an advantage when driving and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such transport.
Finally, by October 2014, the Ministry of Economic Development will include in the list of indicators for assessing the activities of regional authorities criteria reflecting the effectiveness of support for the production of environmentally friendly transport and the development of charging infrastructure.
The market for electric vehicles in Russia is still only being formed - in 2013, about 100 electric vehicles were sold throughout the country.
In early 2014, the import duty on electric vehicles was zeroed out, so sales will be about 500 units, predicts the chief executive officer of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia, Andrei Pankov.
But the fivefold growth does not make electric cars any noticeable: in 2013, according to the Association of European Businesses, 2.78 million cars and light commercial vehicles were sold in Russia.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric cars to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start importing - the company focuses primarily on corporate customers, says Nicolas Remiz, director of strategic planning and partnerships at Renault in Russia.
Most other manufacturers of electric transport took a wait-and-see attitude towards Russia.
Russian manufacturers also have developments of electric vehicles - "", GAZ, "", but the release is scanty.
For example, in January-July 2014, according to ASM-Holding, AvtoVAZ produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low due to the high cost of electric vehicles, admits Sergey Amanov, Director of AvtoVAZ for Engineering, without state support, there will be no breakthrough in this segment.
The development of the Russian market of electric vehicles in addition to the high cost of cars (those electric cars that are sold in Russia, on average, twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) restrains the underdevelopment of the charging infrastructure (refueling stations - units), sighs the general director of "AUTOSTAT" Sergey Tselikov.
Due to the high cost and low rate of cost reduction, electric cars in the next 3-4 years will remain a niche segment of the Russian market, predicts the editor-in-chief of Autoreview Mikhail Podorozhansky, Tselikov agrees with him.
Automakers, by contrast, say that some models of electric vehicles are already close to the cost of conventional ones.
The Russian market of electric vehicles has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that "electromobility" is real; this, in particular, will contribute to the emergence of new charging stations, emphasizes the President of the BMW Group in Russia Wolfgang Schlimme.
Such infrastructure projects are implemented, for example, by the state company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of gas stations are underway with other regions.
According to Vladimir Sofyin, Director of the Rosseti Department, the company believes in the electric vehicle market and is ready to build gas stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric vehicles in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric vehicles of various brands.
In addition, Rosseti as a grid company does not have the right to sell electricity, the possibility of doing this in relation to charging electric vehicles is being worked out.
Pankov believes that the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the electric vehicle market in Russia is the zeroing of customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension and expansion of the preferential list is being worked out.
Replacing the transport tax with an environmental tax (the idea is being discussed and applies to all cars) will also support the market, but not as significantly as customs preferences, Pankov believes.
The transport tax in Russia is small, says Pankov, unlike, for example, Norway, where the tax cut has led to a sharp increase in sales of electric vehicles - now they account for 12% of the market.
In Russia, we also need incentive measures for car owners, for example, free parking in the city center (as has already been done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the possibility of moving electric vehicles along dedicated lanes, which is not yet available in Russia.
