The car recycling program resumed on September 1
From September 1, the program for the disposal of cars is resumed in Russia.
Until December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As explained by the head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov, money is allocated from the limits that have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation by redistribution from other areas of support.
The program will affect all cars older than six years.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a passenger car to 350 thousand rubles for a truck.
Earlier in Russia, a similar program of car recycling has already been operated.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is planned not only to recycle cars to receive a subsequent discount, but also the opportunity, if the car has reached the age of more than six years, to purchase a new one at a discount when handing over the old one to the "trade-in" at the dealer, Interfax reports.
More than 16 billion rubles were spent on the previous federal recycling program, which operated from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011.
Thanks to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 amounted to about 1.2 million units (this is plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
The creator of Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nikki Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case began work on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact has become widely known only now.
The source of inspiration for the game was the events in Ferguson, where there are now protests that began after a policeman killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a name, will be how the information coverage of stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a citizen journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in areas where clashes between the police and the population occur.
The hero can photograph what is happening in different ways, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene in such a way that the police will look like heroes, and the protesters will look like bandits, the police will begin to treat him better and let him go where an ordinary person cannot go.
If he covers events differently, his photographs could turn peaceful protests into a large-scale riot.
Points in the game will need to be scored using the hero's Twitter, in which new subscribers will appear if the photos posted there turn out to be popular.
The game does not yet have a name.
The release date and the platforms on which it will appear are unknown.
Case, however, posted an image demonstrating how an event might change depending on how a photo about it is taken and processed.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been thinking about the concept of such a game for a long time, but initially wanted to devote it not to protests in the United States, but to events in the Gaza Strip.
After he began to collect material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to cover the history of the region.
However, when he saw how the media covered the events in Ferguson, he decided to make a game based on what happened.
Nikki Case is an independent developer who produces browser games.
His most famous project was Coming Out Simulator, released in 2014.
This game, which tells about the events from the biography of Case himself, is devoted to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell about his relationship to homophobic parents.
