The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayut (right) appoints Prawit Wongsuwan (left) as Defense Minister
Thailand's military ruler and prime minister, General Prayut Chan-o-cha, has announced the composition of the country's new cabinet, in which more than a third of positions are held by retired or generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: ministers of defense, finance, foreign affairs and trade.
On Monday, Prayut Chan-o-cha was officially confirmed as prime minister after the King of Thailand officially approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old military man, who seized power in the country in a bloodless coup on May 22, was the only candidate for the premiership.
He was elected Prime Minister at a meeting of Parliament.
Earlier, the army appointed members of parliament.
According to Prayut Chan-o-cha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
It was preceded by six months of demonstrations in which protesters demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra's government.
Officially, Prayut Chan-o-cha will be interim prime minister as the military plans to hold general elections in late 2015.
However, there are fears that the military is trying to consolidate its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22
against the backdrop of complete paralysis of civil power.
The leaders of the main political parties were placed under temporary arrest.
Immediately after the military came to power, they temporarily arrested the country's leading politicians, including Prime Minister Yingluk Shinawatra.
Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis dates back to 2006, when the army removed Yingluk Shinawatra Thaksin's brother as prime minister.
Both are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern regions of the country, which has repeatedly ensured their success in elections.
However, many representatives of the middle class and the metropolitan elite joined the anti-government movement, which since November 2013 has practically paralyzed the country.
No one said that mussels would be better in a salad, I did not promise you this, jokes the waitress from the new Palm brasserie.
We have to formally admit that this is indeed the case, but the mind and stomach remain adamant.
After all, everyone has long known: we say "Belgium" - we mean mussels, we say "mussels" - we mean "Belgium".
Restaurateurs like to thoughtfully state that the success of the institution depends on three factors: this is location, location and once again location.
There are such places, located not only well, but even excellent, but some unlucky.
In short, sitting at the Palm table, I remembered that once there was a cafe "Gorodok" (in honor of the same TV show), then "Odessa-Mama", and also a restaurant "Bojole" and a beer house "Friendship".
Now here again beer, but no longer nostalgic-Soviet, but Belgian.
Above the ground is only the tip of the iceberg: a bar counter and a couple of tables, the rest of the space is devoid of even a hint of sunlight.
But here it is fun, as in the children's room: red, yellow and green walls, multi-colored chairs, instead of windows - TVs, where mermaid girls swim.
Belgian establishments in St. Petersburg are no longer a novelty, so there is something to compare with.
There are eight types of draught beer (260-300 rubles per 0.5 liters) and countless bottled beers (170-1550 rubles).
A sociably positive waitress cheerfully presents the menu, saying that "mussels are hearty large seeds", and it should be noted: it is the service, despite some shortcomings, that is the most positive side of Palm.
The menu is expected in content, but often very unexpected in execution.
Well, who, for example, is given to predict that a meatloaf with Walloon prunes (280 rubles) is actually carpaccio, cut so thinly that parchment paper in comparison with it will seem ugly thick.
You can feel at least some taste only if you rake half a plate at once.
With salads, it's even worse.
The classic Liège (260) would most correctly be recognized as a crime against the Belgian people: some kind of parched iceberg, potatoes boiled once upon a time, sour Kenyan beans, hardened bacon chips plus pickled onions for some reason.
With such a Liège salad you would not wish a meeting on anyone!
The composition of the ingredients of the Belgian salad was partially different, but the impression was also not positive.
If you could still close your eyes to unripe quarters of cherry tomatoes or overcooked mushrooms, then why do mussels look like they have been defrosted and boiled several times in their lifetime!
After all, I already know: there are quite normal White Sea mussels here!
They are served in pans "in the sauce of your choice" (490-560 rubles per 0.5 kg).
Half a dozen sauces, the one made of white wine, celery and carrots, frankly did not set.
There are vegetables, but there is no aroma, and whether there was wine there remains a mystery.
But fritas with homemade mayonnaise are good for mussels.
Chicken waterseed here is not a soup, thick to such an extent that depending on your mood you can decide whether the first or second course is in front of you, but just a pleasant creamy soup.
It was stated that the rabbit was cooked in beer sauce by a local chef, and nothing was said about rosemary.
In fact, the situation turned out to be diametrically opposite: rosemary drowned out everything.
There was an impression that this rabbit during his lifetime was fed exclusively rosemary bushes, which is why the meat acquired such an unusual aroma.
But at the same time, a wonderful - no, just an excellent pear in a caramelized crust was attached to the rabbit leg.
Waffles in Palm offer not only sweet, but also hearty - with beef, chicken or bacon and cheese (220-280).
The maple sauce was unnecessarily watery and the waffles were dry.
But the manager who came to the table very informally asked about the lunch impressions.
So, it's worth coming again.
