A genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
The British woman said that she spent many years thinking that she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Caryn Rogers spent much of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that cause damage to nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK has reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, uncertain gait and twitched toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition whose prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and would die before she turned 30.
The mother-of-two, now 51, said: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do what others did.
I fell every day and it took me more time.
I've never been able to roller skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical record when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where I shouldn't, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I received the information back, I was shocked and experienced the worst panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turned 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that span.
I went through it alone and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought and asked her doctor about it.
He just got up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease because you would already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that is much less life-threatening.
After several genetic examinations, she was diagnosed with CMT.
"When he explained what CMT was, I thought I had pulled out a lucky ticket," she said.
The CHARITY CMT UK has announced a month of information on CMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on Washington Zone entrepreneurs is growing as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased modestly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study released last week, and companies in the Washington Zone are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on business by state and locally increased 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when bills declined, in 2009 and 2010.
Taxes levied by the state rose faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the state's Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, generates the least amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the rise in tax revenues is caused by a return to the previous level of real estate value of companies, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years when growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large share of these revenues come from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it appears that the same thing is happening in the Washington Zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in property taxes by state and local last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 — an increase of 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return in property values has no similar effect on the growth of tax revenues by state and locally in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies' tax bills.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned either by the government or by nonprofit organizations that don't pay property taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the state's TaxAtion Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes, to pay for the same services that are available in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs' incomes also appear to be on the mend, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared state corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although the trends are in one direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a below-average rise in tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) of 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs by state and at the local level and, in general, a more favorable climate when it comes to taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could bring the income tax rate for businesses to even 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington Zone seem to be doing better and thus paying more taxes by state and locally, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid as individual income tax by small business owners — the transitional structure under which most small firms operate — in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher growth rate than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues from state and local governments up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington zone may lag behind, as the reduction in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
