Their debut self-titled album received 100,000 pre-orders a few months before its release, and the contract for its release is in the portfolio of the major label Warner Music.
Given the current deplorable situation in the music market, the situation is out of the ordinary, because we are not talking about a new Lana Del Rey or another sweet-voiced representative of the "new R'n'B", but about a duo of bullish-looking Britons playing with the level of volume and intensity that was last in vogue a couple of decades ago.
In general, the stakes for the first album in connection with all the above circumstances were especially high and have already been fully justified.
The duo has not in vain taken a name for itself, which until then could be encroached upon only by very desperate hairy metalheads, and the blood of which kings flows, as it seems to them, in their veins, is also understandable.
This, of course, is primarily about the heroes of the past level of Led Zeppelin: like the great quartet, Royal Blood aims to shake up the stagnant blood of British rock, bringing it to a new height.
It is probably too early to make predictions about the success of this enterprise, but something can already be asserted.
A dozen songs that fit into a little over thirty minutes is not so much a demonstration of phenomenal composer's talent as a confident and powerful declaration of intent.
Some advantages of individual numbers, of course, can not be denied: for example, the pilot single "Out Of The Black" is characterized by the fact that it is remembered not by a melodic line, but by a drum part.
Musicians jokingly say that this song is generally easier to knock than to sing.
It is also worth highlighting the powerful "Little Monster" and the album's closing composition "Better Strangers" with a Shakespearean quote in the title.
However, the truth is that each of these songs will sound great at a party of fans of hard rock, but when played in a row, they merge into a more or less homogeneous canvas.
And that's not necessarily a bad thing, quite the opposite.
The strength of Royal Blood is that they do not claim the laurels of the new Lennon and McCartney (rather mark in the successors of Motörhead), but have brought numerous rock duos out of the ghetto of indie clubs.
Their music, despite some variety, is created for stadiums, in a room designed for less than a couple of thousand people, it is obviously cramped.
The secret is partly in the cunning use of bass, which replaced the guitar in the usual format, invented in the early noughties the White Stripes.
However, it's not only about the instruments, but also about the very approach to songwriting.
The heroes of the noughties with great difficulty got out of the postmodern paradigm, with great reluctance they went to recognize themselves not just as epigons, but as independent creative units.
Royal Blood already sounds so powerful and brazen that this pressure successfully drapes some secondary and hard-headed musical material.
And after all, who says rock has to be smart?
