Deputies proposed to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of the initiative, the data of Russians can not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
A draft law has been submitted to the State Duma providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is posted in the database of legislative activities of the lower house.
Its authors were State Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Fair Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (Communist Party).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more prompt and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the safety of personal data and the observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is in a hurry of parliamentarians, obliges to store in the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of violating sites - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, Leonid Levin, said that he sees no problems for postponing the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies that today already provide their servers."
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see any problems - they will receive technological opportunities for placement," Levin summed up.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association for Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is adopted, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation - the right to dispose of their own data, imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
The STATEMENT of RAEC emphasizes that a more effective measure would be the creation of a mechanism for informing the user about where the recording is carried out, systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose in which territory these actions will be performed.
The adoption of similar bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries led to the departure of global services and to significant economic losses.
