Tricky Ways to Save on University Textbooks
With the cost of university textbooks exceeding $1,000 a year for many students, Matt Schroeder, who will soon be in his sophomore year, has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He developed a system of how to borrow books from undergraduates, offering them nominal compensation to delay their sale.
"My math textbook, which usually costs $180, I got for a semester for $10 and a 'Chick-fil-A' cookie," says Schroeder, 19, who attends Covenant College in Georgia.
The necessary literature for last semester would have cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
According to the College Council, the average student spends more than $1200 a year on textbooks and teaching supplies, but students have a range of options for reducing these costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online shopping and creative ideas like Schroeder's system.
Book rentals are becoming increasingly popular, allowing students to use the book throughout the semester, and are often substantially cheaper than buying them.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, reports that book rentals have doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of books in university bookstores were rented during last spring semester, says Nibo vice president Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of all books are purchased from university bookstores, according to the national association of university stores.
Here's an introductory course on the best ways to make a good deal.
Purchase in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one-third of what you'll see at a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of "Mathematical Analysis" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $ 290 according to the price list, but a new copy can be purchased for $ 239.99 on the website of Chegg.com, which specializes in selling textbooks.
Buying used
If you don't mind other people's marks or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
"Mathematical Analysis" sells for $93.49 in used form on Chegg.com.
Matt Casaday, 25, a fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid Amazon.com 42 cents for a second-hand copy of the textbook "Strategic Decisions in Media: Understanding the Business Side of advertising."
The book sold for $48 new.
Teachers such as Ingrid Bracey, director of the College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Emherst, invite students to ask their professors whether previous editions can be used.
Sometimes updates are insignificant for classes.
In such cases, old editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the cost of the latest edition.
In addition to chegg and Amazon, Half.com owned by eBay Inc. is a popular alternative for buying used books.
Hire
It's worth considering renting textbooks if you handle them well enough, don't forget to return them, and don't want to keep them after the course is over.
You can save more than 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent a "Mathematical Analysis" for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the store where you get the books, including any fines you may be charged for notes, underlining, and damage.
If you rent a book, remember: if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented, acquiring an electronic license for a certain period from distributors, for example, Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
Renting a "Mathematical Analysis" on the Chegg.com website for six months will cost about $ 61.
Bracey says that literature students can often find the best prices, as many classic works can now be downloaded for free, whereas literature in the natural and engineering sciences can be quite expensive.
No matter what, look around.
Joe Gault, 29, who is about to start his studies at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using an ISBN number to find out the prices of the book, as this ensures that you are looking for exactly the text you need.
Before you place an order online, Says Gault, be sure to check to see if the book is actually in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
Delivery of the book he had purchased was delayed by four weeks, and eventually he paid the full price at the university bookstore.
