"Europrotocol" instead of a traffic police certificate
Payments for casco can be received without a certificate of the traffic police - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "Europrotocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed draft instructions, according to which, from September 1 of this year, in order to receive payments for casco, an insured motorist will be able to do without a traffic police certificate.
This, however, refers only to those cases when the accident was registered according to the "Europrotocol" without the participation of the traffic police.
That is, if only two cars were involved in the accident, there are no naturally injured persons, the damage does not exceed the established limit and both drivers have reached an agreement on the question of who is the culprit of the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the "Europrotocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The bottom line is that often even with minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be registered according to the "Europrotocol", drivers who are in an accident call the traffic police.
After all, in the presence of a casco policy, it was impossible to receive compensation for it without a traffic police certificate.
The parameters prescribed in the draft directive are precisely designed to eliminate this obstacle to the introduction of the "Europrotocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment for casco in connection with an accident issued without traffic police officers should not be lower than the limit on the "Europrotocol".
But at the same time, it cannot be higher than the limit defined in the casco insurance contract.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically capable of unloading both traffic police officers and roads.
But, most likely, neither motorists nor insurers will be delighted with it.
The latter are already talking about a serious threat of fraud growth, which may result from the introduction of new rules for casco payments.
As for drivers, it is difficult to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the original Russian conservatism.
The driver in most cases will wait for hours for the inspector to arrange a minor accident, because it is more reliable.
And it remains to be seen what will be easier - to defeat the scammers or to convince drivers of the reliability of the "Europrotocol".
The savings certificate will be made nominal and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban bearer savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban bearer savings certificates.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since it is not necessary to make contributions to the deposit insurance agency (DIA) fund.
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to DIA estimates, control 98% of the core market, will suffer from it.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency's calculations, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the DIA explains, is that customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of its license, try to get money from the DIA.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in the event of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," the DIA said.
The problem, of course, is far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, since they do not have the right to compensation from the state by law.
If the fact was that the instrument is not insured in the DIA, metal accounts would be banned along with it, in which citizens' funds are accounted for in grams of one of four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one has yet encroached on their existence.
The fact is most likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security, which in fact can act as a quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing out, such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill states that a savings certificate must necessarily be a registered security, which must be stored in the depository.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of an irrevocable deposit, which bankers have long dreamed of, is introduced.
