Sinful Boredom
Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez's Film Sin City 2: The Woman To Kill for did not make the revolution you would expect.
The first Sin City (2005), filmed with the minimal but symbolic involvement of Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between cinema, comics, and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it destroys the "thesis - antithesis - synthesis" chain that is fundamental for modern thinking (if you understand the noir universe by the thesis, and the comic book space by antithesis).
From now on, it should be read: "thesis - antithesis - chaos".
Sin City 2 is chaotic on both a dramatic and philosophical level: both times it is chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the characters are familiar from the first "City", although, behold, the thug Marv (Mickey Rourke), I remember, ended his life in the electric chair, and here, nothing, only manages to snatch - in the role of a kind of people's vigilante - from the air knives and other axes with nooses.
But the old people are literally elbowed by newcomers, as if they broke into the city from some other film, about the meaning and plot of which the audience is asked not to worry.
So, the super-lucky player Johnny (Joseph Gordon-Levitt) has his own story, shamelessly cut short by the authors at the most interesting place.
Her own - from the lustfully frigid Eve Lord (Eva Green) and for something avenging her Dwight (Josh Brolin).
But this confusion, in which Dwight, say, cannot be distinguished from Johnny in person - especially since the faces, like other parts of the body, the characters are demolished with inexorable regularity - is not a problem or even half the trouble.
These are not people, we understand that these are noir archetypes: a fatal bitch, an overly confident player, a detective who fell into the "honey trap" of sex, a corrupt ghoul senator.
Well, when the archetype waltzes with the archetype and the archetype drives, then this is no longer a movie, but read that abstract painting.
And asking abstract painting questions about the logic of the plot is ridiculous.
In addition, even in this turbulent world, there is something permanent.
The battle whores from the first "City" still hold a circular defense against the forces of darkness besieging their native slums.
And the ghost of Detective Hartigan is a no-no, and will look at the light, and Bruce Willis is always a pleasure to look at.
The main problem with Sin City 2 is different.
Frank Miller was good because as a draftsman he talentedly combined comic book and noir, and as a director he turned the idea of how to transfer comics to the screen.
Comic book and noir are two aggressively opposed "realities".
The phenomenon of the comic in its modern form was born in the late 1920s, at the same time when Dashiell Hammett's novels Bloody Harvest (1929), The Maltese Falcon (1930) and The Glass Key (1931) created a canon of noir, then called the hard-boiled school- "cool school".
Well, or pulp fiction.
Comics have given Hollywood many dozens of heroes: from the sailor Popeye - the spinach eater, who gives him heroic strength, Superman, Batman and detective Dick Tracy to the Hulk, Thor, Spider-Man and other "avengers".
But in any movie based on comics, there was something flawed: the drawn characters stubbornly did not want to overgrow the screen flesh, remained pretenders in the "real" world around them willy-nilly.
Simply put, they were completely devoid of "existence."
Noir, on the other hand, is the most existential genre of world literature.
After the World Wars, the traditional novel – with experiences, characters, family scandals and historical background – lost all credibility.
What Kind of Forsythes, what Thibault and Rougon-Makkar, which even Bolkonsky and Rostov are even conceivable after Verdun, Auschwitz and Hiroshima?
Such a novel peacefully mutated into the format of a soap opera, and a criminal - that is, by definition marginal - novel rose to the level of philosophical prose.
Hammett learned from his own skin what it was like to work as a nurse at the front.
He was a communist.
As, by the way, were at least close to the Communist Party and such pillars of the genre as writers Horace McCoy and Jim Thompson, directors Jules Dassin, Joseph Losey, Edward Dmitrik.
Therefore, the noir, the archetype of which they have set, is firstly rude and cynical, and secondly, it is purely social.
It's almost an American version of socialist realism.
The first Sin City was remarkable precisely because it unnaturally but organically combined the comic with noir.
For the first time on the screen, the comic came to life, not at all ashamed of its graphic nature, and did not pretend to be a "real" film.
The darkness of a corrupt world, where a cardinal ordered assassinations and a senator covered up a monstrous sadistic son, was well worthy of Hammett's pen.
And picturesque details like the severed heads with which the sadist decorated his nest, the pen of the brilliant James Ellroy, the author of "Black Orchid" and the best - that is, declaratively nauseating - representative of the neo-noir.
Sin City 2 is not even a digression, but a capitulation of Miller--Rodriguez's radical style to the comic book tradition.
Probably, this was largely due to 3D technology.
When you watch the second "Sin City", you feel yourself imprisoned in a glass ball, inside of which the snow fills the toy cloaca.
However, most often it is not snow, but bloody scum, but by and large, what is the difference?
Well, there is nothing to say about sociality.
After all, it is possible only when somewhere, somewhere in our country sometimes, albeit on the side of a dirty swamp, but there is a normal world where you can return a girl who walked along a crooked path or, say, tell inconsolable parents that her destroyer is punished.
When there is no place for anything but sin in the city of sin, then sin is no longer a sin, but the norm.
Boring as any norm.
The chaos of Sin City 2 is just boring.
To be fair, the domestic rental gave this bland sin a small but peppercorn.
The credits warn that the film contains harmful smoking scenes.
In relation to the spectacle, in the most vegetarian episode of which a person's fingers are broken with tongs, it smacks of hellish humor.
Hammett would have liked it.
