A potential way to steal photos of nude celebrities has been discovered
Mass hacking of star accounts may have been made through a vulnerability in the Find My Phone application.
A potential scenario for the development of events was described by the resource The Next Web.
On the resource Github was published a script in Python, which allowed you to select passwords to the service Find My Phone Apple.
This service allows you to track the location of the iPhone.
To access it, the same bundle of login and password Apple ID is used as to access the Apple iCloud cloud, from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script allowed you to brute-force to find out the password from Find My Phone.
With this method, all sorts of combinations of characters are sequentially entered, starting with the most commonly used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that in the Find My Phone service, the number of password options entered is unlimited.
With the correct organization of the security system, after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password, the account should be blocked and inform the user about the hacking attempt.
Due to the vulnerability, users did not receive any messages about trying to guess the password to their account.
Hackers learned the password from the Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to a message by a Hackapp user on Twitter, the vulnerability was discovered two days ago, on Saturday, and a scripting program was written to it to guess passwords.
At the moment, the vulnerability is closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted the user of Hackapp and he noted that the above-mentioned vulnerability is typical for many services, but noted that he has no evidence that such a vulnerability was used to access the account of the "stars".
