Putin granted Russian citizenship to Ukrainian pentathlete
Russian President Vladimir Putin granted Russian citizenship to the famous Ukrainian athlete Anna Buryak.
The corresponding decree was published on the Internet portal of legal information.
At the beginning of this year, the athlete moved to Russia for permanent residence and appealed to the Modern Pentathlon Federation with a request to give her the opportunity to play for the Russian national team.
In 2013, she won two stages of the World Cup, won a silver medal at the European Championships in the individual championship and became the world champion in the mixed relay, which is one of the new types of the program in this sport.
It holds a leading position in the current season.
According to the rules, in order to perform at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, she will need to obtain special permission from the Ukrainian Olympic Committee.
Anna Buryak is not the first Ukrainian athlete to change her citizenship.
In July, Vladimir Putin decided to issue a Russian passport to chess player Ekaterina Lagno, a native of Lviv, who is a two-time champion of Europe (2005, 2008), the world in blitz (2010) and rapid chess (2014).
As part of the women's team of Ukraine, the athlete became the winner of the Chess Olympiad in Turin (2006), the World Team Championship in Astana (2013) and the European Team Championship in Warsaw (2013).
The ICR stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 crash in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICR) terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline.
This was reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the aircraft commander and flight engineer.
Forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of the approach to landing, the failure of the crew to perform standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintentional exit of the engines to increased direct thrust speeds.
The Tu-204 aircraft of Red Wings Airlines, following the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 during landing at Moscow's Vnukovo Airport.
The aircraft rolled out of the runway and caught fire.
The aircraft commander, co-pilot and flight engineer were killed at the scene.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they later died from their injuries.
Three more flight attendants, hospitalized with serious injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, serious bodily injuries were received by the driver of the car, who was moving at the time of the disaster on the Kiev highway.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the crash, the transport prosecutor's office conducted an inspection in Red Wings, during which numerous violations were revealed.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
