Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional human emotion.
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for mankind, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the United States found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions — shifted and lowered eyebrows, outstretched lips, swollen nostrils — are the same in all cultures, and even children blind from birth who have never seen it do so, notes the study's lead author, Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion arose to effectively conduct disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can cause to another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his terms, and he conveys this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
Researchers have found confirmation of their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and go to assault, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer forceful methods of resolving conflicts to peaceful ones.
Starting from the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry facial expression should present the angry individual as powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thereby force him to agree to his conditions as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated on a computer faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or missing, and showed them to informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or a forward chin individually did not make the face angry, the person depicted with such features was recognized by the physically stronger participants in the study unanimously.
Human anger, as in animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one's own power, forcing one to agree and submit.
A person inflates his nostrils and purses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
"Anger is "triggered" by the interlocutor's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing, "said anthropologist John Tooby.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the tv and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate in 2014 from the federal budget 250 million rubles to the autonomous non-profit organization "Television and Radio Company "Crimea"".
This is stated in the draft government resolution prepared by the department, which was reviewed by Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the draft, subsidies from the federal budget will be used "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment."
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to be used to re-equip the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central control room and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of a fiber-optic communication line (FOCL) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget funds provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company "Krym" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the television and radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "TV and Radio Company "Crimea"" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
